Beijing's natural ecology continues to be good, attracting more than 500 wildlife cities to "settle" - a new network.
2020-07-26 05:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth newspaper by Wang Seok-seok.
The natural ecology of the capital continues to attract wildlife cities to settle.
There are over 500 species of wildlife in Beijing.
The reporter Wang Bin, a Beijing youth journalist, has learned from the Greening of the City Gardens Bureau that in recent years, as the natural ecological environment of the capital continues to improve, the variety and number of wildlife have continued to increase.
The number of terrestrial vertebrate wildlife living in Beijing has increased to more than 500, including the protection of animals at the national level, such as brown horse chickens and black storks, as well as the protection of animals at the national level at the secondary level, such as antelopes, giant swans, cranes and thirams.
Whether it is an urban forest planted in the ring or a small wetland embedded in a building, it not only brings nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wildlife to “settle” the city.
In the middle of the summer season, the Pine Mountains, located in the Yan Mountain Mountains in the north-west of the Yanqing region, are vibrant in their national nature reserves.
And one of them played around the mountains, and two of them fought each other.
Turning back, a wild boar could not resist the “strucking” on his body and was strutting the bark. The Director of the National Service for Nature Reserves in Pine Mountains, Mr. Hu Xiaoli, described the fact that, as of the end of 2019, in a green sea of more than 6,200 hectares, 178 species of wildlife, including the conservation of animal golden eagles at the national level and the protection of animal spoon chickens and euphoria at the national level, could be found in nearly one third of all wildlife species in the city.
“In Pine Mountain, wildlife is the true master, and our staff can only be considered as their bodyguard.”
According to Hu Chongli, in order to gain a field view of wildlife in the protected areas, more than 30 professional rangers patrol each day along 16 well-designed protection routes, and a monthly “turning circle” takes almost the entire protected area all day.
“In the course of the inspection, not only the recording of biodiversity, but also the installation of artificial bird nests, the rescue of injured wildlife, the installation of infra-field infrared cameras, etc..”
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in the Pine Hill National Nature Reserve to document the state of life of wildlife in the forest.
As the biodiversity of protected areas has increased over the years, the presence of wild animals in the lens has increased, leopard cats, gills and pigs have become “resident guests” and the “opportunity” of protected animals at the national level has increased.
Zhang Zhi Minh, Head of the Wildlife and Wetlands Conservation Division of the Beijing Park Greening Bureau, described the increase in terrestrial vertebrate wildlife from 461 species in 1994 to over 500 today, and the continuous increase in species and numbers of wildlife in Beijing in recent years.
The presence of wildlife in cities is becoming more common and is closely linked to the recent escalation of greening in the capital city.
In particular, the new round of reforestation of million acres, which began in 2018, proposes to reshape the urban environment, upgrade the ecological function of green lands and highlight the concept of “near nature”.
The plan seeks to interact with the surrounding green areas to facilitate wildlife “visit friends” and to plant trees that are also a source of honey and food for animals.
