Poland will withdraw from the European Treaty on the Prevention of Violence against Women
The Ministry of Justice of Poland indicated on Saturday that Poland would take steps next week to withdraw from the European Treaty on the Prevention of Violence against Women.
The right-wing Government Cabinet of Poland stated that the treaty required schools to teach students about gender issues, which violated the rights of parents.
A press conference organized by the Polish Minister of Justice, Joblo, said that his Ministry of Justice would submit a request on Monday to the Ministry of Labour and Family to start withdrawing from the treaty.
The treaty is known as the Istanbul Convention.
“The treaty contains elements of a morphological nature which we consider to be harmful”.
The Polish ruling law is closely allied with the Party for Justice and its partners in the ruling coalition and the Roman Catholic Church, advocating a conservative social agenda.
The hostility to homosexual rights was one of the main themes of the successful re-election campaign of Polish President Duda this month.
On Friday, thousands of Poles, most of them women, held protests against withdrawal from the Convention in Warsaw and other cities.
One of the organizers of the protest, Lempat, stated in a protest march in Warsaw that “the purpose of withdrawing from the treaty was to legalize domestic violence”.
A number of protesters carried banners that read “The Law and Justice Party is the hell of women”.
The Law and Justice Party has long complained about the Istanbul Convention.
The Convention was ratified by Poland ' s previous intermediate Government in 2015.
The Law and Justice Party Government stated that the treaty did not respect religion and required the teaching of liberal social policies in schools.
To date, however, the party has not decided to withdraw from the Convention.
