The United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on 24 December, requiring an emergency inspection of approximately 2,000 Boeing 737 NG and 737 Classic passenger aircraft registered in the United States, on the grounds that the erosion of the aircraft ' s air-closure valves could lead to engine parking in the air.
According to the Federal Aviation Office, four reports of air parking of 737 NG and 737 Classic passenger engines have been received so far, leading to an urgent inspection request for passenger aircraft parked for seven consecutive days or more and for passenger aircraft that have so far flown less than 11 times after re-entry.
The Federal Aviation Agency warned that if all the 5th stop valves of the passenger engines were corrupted, they might be stuck in the opening position, resulting in a complete loss of power and inability to restart the engine.
This aviation regulator ordered that, once the stop valves were found to be corrupted, the air operator must replace this critical component before the passenger aircraft is again operational.
Boeing responded later that day that the outbreak of the new coronary outbreak had led to a reduction in the need for travel, resulting in a number of passenger aircraft being blocked or less used, and that the “closure valves were more vulnerable to erosion.”
Boeing also stated that it had been recommended to the air operator to inspect the passenger aircraft covered by the instructions and that if problems were identified, Boeing would provide assistance in such areas as overhauling and replacing stop valves.
