For the first time, the United States launched a countervailing survey on China with an “undervalued RMB exchange rate”
In response to a recent announcement by the United States Department of Commerce, it was decided to launch an anti-dumping countervailing investigation into Zatra (belt belt) products originating in China and an investigation into the “undervalued RMB exchange rate” project.
The Ministry of Commerce of China stated that this was the first time that the United States had investigated the so-called “underestimation of the RMB exchange rate” project in a countervailing neutral case, which China strongly opposed.
In particular, the Ministry of Commerce issued a press release on the night of the 23rd meeting in which it stated that China had introduced a system of regulated floating exchange rates based on demand and supply, with reference to a basket of currencies, and that the market played a decisive role in exchange rate formation.
The press release emphasized that the exchange rate of the renminbi was generally at a reasonable level of equilibrium and was not underestimated.
Since 2005, the renminbi has accumulated an appreciation of over 17 per cent against the United States dollar.
According to data published by the Bank for International Settlements, between the beginning of 2005 and May 2020, the effective exchange rate of the renminbi appreciated by 38 per cent and the real effective exchange rate by 49 per cent, the strongest currency of the G-20 economies and one of the largest currencies globally.
The Department of Commerce noted that the exchange rate issue went beyond the competence of members to conduct countervailing investigations under World Trade Organization rules.
In February this year, the United States amended its legislation to conduct countervailing investigations of foreign exchange rates, which have been criticized for violating WTO rules.
The press release stated that even under United States legislation, there were numerous errors in the content of the applicant ' s complaint, which did not have the necessary countervailing elements, such as financial support, benefit award and exclusivity.
China urges the United States to comply with existing international rules and to stop conducting countervailing investigations into the so-called “underestimation of the RMB exchange rate”.
Increased tensions in relations between China and the United States led to a sharp drop in the 22-day exchange rate between offshore and the United States dollar, both of which fell at a level of 7.0 yuan.
Whether this move by the United States Department of Commerce is intended to push the renminbi up is a matter of concern.
The current exchange rate of the renminbi against the United States dollar rose by 7.0 to 6.9961 on 23 days.
The median value of the RMB against the United States dollar, which is officially regulated, was reduced by 17 basic points on 24 days, to 6.9938.
