LEWIS FAMILY: John Lewis is a warrior who fights for the weakest.
John Lewis, a member of the United States Congress, was remembered as a fighter “to fight for the weakest” at his memorial on Saturday (25 July).
A public memorial to Lewis has been held in Alabama since Saturday.
There are two memorials on the first day.
On Saturday, at a public memorial at the University of Troy, Alabama, five brothers and sisters of Lewis and a grandson spoke of a man who was full of love, fearless and family-oriented.
The youngest brother of Lewis, Henry “Grant”, Lewis, said at the meeting, “He's dedicated his life to helping others.”
Samuel Lewis said that his mother had warned John “not to cause trouble, not to cause trouble”.
He added that John did not heed the mother's warning, saying, “We all know that John always gets in trouble, always gets in trouble, but that's because he's sticking to the right thing, and that's good trouble.”
The brothers and sisters of Lewis remind people at the memorial that John's most famous argument is to create “good trouble”, that is, not to avoid causing trouble in the interests of justice.
John had applied for the University of Troy (Troy University), where he was born in Troy, Alabama, but at that time the University of Troy, which was all white schools, refused his application.
John Lewis, who was evangelizing chickens on his farm as a child, later obtained a degree in religion and philosophy from Fisk University.
Many years later, the University of Troy awarded Lewis an honorary doctorate.
Senator Doug Jones, a congressional senator from Alabama, said that the current protesters “are protesting peacefully and non-violently”, as Lewis did in the civil rights movement.
Jones said, "Even though President Trump knocked over a boat and described all the protesters as thugs, he was wrong.
The protesters are patriots who want the United States to move towards a more equal nation.”
A six-day series of events to commemorate Lewis will culminate this week at the funeral in Georgia.
On Saturday, Lewis' coffin was stopped at a public memorial at the University of Troy, and people came to pay tribute to the civil rights movement pioneer.
Later on Saturday, a private ceremony paid tribute to him in a small church in Selma, Alabama, followed by a public memorial.
On Sunday, Lewis' body will pass through the Edmund Pettus Bridge of Selma.
In 1965, he and the demonstrators demanding the right to vote of the black people were beaten in front of the bridge by the Alabama State police, who also gave tear gas to the demonstrators.
Lewis was almost killed.
The day after that is called “bloody Sunday”.
Lewis' remains will be transported to Montgomery, the capital of Alabama.
Mayor Steven Reed encouraged people to line up on the sidewalk and finish this last journey with Lewis.
At the same time, officials are required to wear masks and maintain social distance when requesting public participation.
The Governor of Alabama, Kay Ivey, ordered half a flag down on Saturdays and Sundays to commemorate Lewis.
In the commemoration of almost a week, Lewis ' remains will be divided into the Alabama State Council Building in the city of Montgomery, the Georgia State Council Building in Atlanta, and the United States Congress Building in Washington for a short period of time for the public to express their condolences.
The Speaker of the United States House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Senate majority leader, Mitch McConnell, announced last week that one could come to the United States Congress Building on Monday and Tuesday to pay tribute to Lewis.
As a result of the coronary virus epidemic, a public event in memory of Lewis will be held outdoors.
