Three-year-old kid college playgrounds are wrecked and paid for before bringing charges against the school?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Daily Journal of the Rule of Law
The playground was smashed and the children were paid for and then sued.
□ The correspondent of this newspaper, Zhao Yifan
When a 3-year-old young Man played in a university playground, Chen was accidentally hit in the head by a softball team during a pitch.
After some compensation, Mr. Wen, his father, brought the school before the court as his legal representative, requested an apology from the school where the incident had taken place and paid a total of $20,000 for medical care, moral damage relief, etc.
Recently, after hearing the case, the People ' s Court of the Haidian District of Beijing decided to dismiss the plaintiff ' s claim on the basis that the school had set up a safety net in the playground at the time of the incident, that it had fulfilled its obligation to provide adequate security and that Chen had paid compensation.
Mr. Wen claimed that during the summer vacation of 2019, he was playing in the school playground with young Man, while the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the risks associated with this, Mr. Siu Man, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents are operating within the safe zone designated by the softball team.
However, since then, the softball team member, Chen Yai, left his hand when he pitched the ball, causing the softball to fly across the net to the safety zone described above and hit the back of the small text.
Mr. Wen immediately took Siu Wen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with a head trauma.
According to Mr. Wen, the facilities at the school stadium did not meet the relevant security requirements and did not effectively manage the teams and related facilities.
The school ' s negligence has led to the above-mentioned events, causing great physical and psychological suffering and causing greater suffering to its families, for which the school is legally responsible.
In response, the school argued that it had installed a safety net in the playground and had posted regulations, training notices informing it that it was necessary to enter the playground at a safe distance from the training site and to alert itself to its safety, and that the plaintiff could not prove that the school was “not fulfilling its safety obligations” and therefore did not accept compensation.
The court concluded that the premises in question were those open to the public free of charge by the university, and that while there was a safety and security obligation for the management of the playground, such a security obligation would have to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school had installed a network in the playground and had fulfilled its obligation to provide adequate safety and security, and Chen had paid Xiaowen more than $2,000 in compensation for various losses such as medical expenses, transportation expenses and so on, in accordance with a previous compensation agreement.
Later, the parents again claimed compensation for the school, which was not justified by law, and the court decided to dismiss all the plaintiff ' s claims.
Following the delivery of the judgement, neither party appealed, and the judgement has now entered into force.
Under article 37 of our law on liability for torts, schools, as managers of public places, have a duty of safety and security; in the case of damage caused by the actions of third persons, third persons bear responsibility for violations, while those in public places who fail to fulfil their duty of safety and security should bear the corresponding supplementary responsibility.
The judge stated that, as managers of public places, who were most likely to know the actual situation of the site as a whole, to foresee the risks and damage that might occur, and thus to take the necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of the loss or to mitigate the extent of the damage, and to avoid and mitigate the lowest cost of the damage, the law imposed on them the corresponding obligation to safeguard the performance of social activities.
In the present case, the safety and security obligations of schools should be commensurate with the social activities they engage in, in particular, the basic security measures and the obligation to inform about hidden risks, for groups of people who do not enter the playgrounds free of charge to the public.
It is also inappropriate in judicial practice to impose excessive security obligations on public administrators.
If the school has adopted a safety net and is obliged to inform, it can be assumed that the school is free from fault and is not legally liable.
In addition, the liability of managers of public places, such as schools, for violations committed by third parties, even if they fail to meet their security obligations, is a supplement to compensation for damages, and, under the recently enacted Civil Code, the administrator may also recover compensation from the third party after assuming additional liability.
Thus, in such an incident, the victim should not extend the claim after having received compensation from the direct infringer.
