"The Lancet" praises China's efforts to combat the disease and encourages countries to learn from the experience of China.
According to the 25-year-old Lancet magazine, China, a country of 1.4 billion people of similar size to Europe or the United States, is effectively controlling the new coronary epidemic at this stage, without further widespread transmission and to a large extent controlling the epidemic at home.
According to the article, China has invested heavily in domestic research and public health construction for more than a decade, which has made it much more prepared for the new crown than for the SARS of that year.
According to the author, at the time of the SARS outbreak in 2002, China was initially under-prepared, especially since the pathogen was uncertain.
When the new coronary virus was discovered in December 2019, Chinese scientists were soon able to identify the type of virus and, on 11 January 2020, shared genomic sequencing data with the international community.
By the end of January, doctors from mainland China and Hong Kong had described the clinical characteristics of the virus and warned the world of the threat of the new crown virus through research papers published in The Lancet.
China has also been at the forefront of vaccine research, which has been carried out very quickly and strictly through close cooperation within the country in the event of a state of emergency declared by the State. In May and July, respectively, China published the results of early trials of its new crown vaccine.
China ' s experience had shown that it was important to invest in national health and research systems and to improve laboratory capacity effectively.
This is the basis for a rapid and effective national response to health emergencies and global health security.
Other countries, especially low- and middle-income countries, deserve to learn and learn.
Moreover, China ' s experience has shown that, on the basis of strong research, strong high-level and decisive science-based sound decision-making is necessary to effectively control the new coronary epidemic.
The article stressed that Governments and their leaders must respect science, understand its value and act on it in the best interests of society.
In the early days of the outbreak, the Chinese National Guard commissioned three groups of infectious disease specialists to travel to Wuhan to investigate the risks and spread of the new crown virus, whose recommendations provided the basis for the decision to “seal the city” in Wuhan on 23 January; the Government's decision was quickly taken and implemented as soon as experts had raised the need and urgency to build the square-hull hospital; and the wide participation of the community and the population had enabled the epidemic to be brought under control quickly and effectively.
The article concludes by emphasizing the need for countries to strengthen global cooperation and joint responses to global health emergencies.
