The membrane separation technology helps break the greenhouse effect - the new net.
Membrane separation technology helps break the greenhouse effect.
Map of new hybrid base-mass membrane preparation techniques
Reporter Swe: Recently, the Atmospheric Environment and Bioenergy Team of Tianjin University made significant progress in developing new technologies for the preparation of mixed base membranes for carbon dioxide capture in the context of membrane separation.
The results were published as a cover article in the international journal Greenhouse Gases: Science and Technology.
The greenhouse effect is a major environmental problem plaguing human development, and CO2 emissions are responsible for the greenhouse effect.
The efficient capture and use of human emissions of carbon dioxide is the focus of scientists.
The membrane separation method is an emerging carbon dioxide capture technique that separates carbon dioxide gases with the help of membrane materials and is characterized by energy efficiency and simplicity of operation.
How to make membrane material “deep breath” and improve the efficiency of gas separation is a bottleneck to capture carbon dioxide using membrane separation.
The scientific team at Tianjin University has been innovative in exploring the effects of different solvents on membrane gas separation performance through repeated experiments.
Experimental results have shown that the use of N-methylacne as a solvent has resulted in a more even distribution of carbon nanopipes in membrane materials, which are “better ventilated” and have effectively improved the gas separation efficiency and rate of membrane materials.
The composite base membrane, prepared with this new technology, allows CO2 separation performances close to the theoretical separation cap of the current membrane material.
“New technologies provide new ideas for membrane separation methods to capture CO2.”
Li Yun, member of the Atmospheric Environment and Bioenergy Team at Tianjin University, said: “We hope that this technology will provide strong support to future coal-fired power plants and chemical industries in dealing with flue gases and play a major role in areas such as control of greenhouse gas emissions.”
Before you volunteer, understand what a professional grader is.
2020-07-27 02:22:36 Source: Chongqing Morning News
You know what a professional is before you volunteer.
Each year, students or parents fill in a higher examination because of their lack of knowledge of the terminology involved in the voluntary submission, thus affecting the voluntary filing.
This year, Beijing University of Transport, Beijing University of Science and Technology, Beijing University of Post and Telecommunications, Beijing Forestry University, Beijing Chemical University and five universities jointly launched a 2020 admission policy to eliminate professional differentials.
What does a poor professional level mean and what is the significance of voluntary filing?
There are three ways the rules of professional assignment.
Experts reminded that before volunteering, it was important to read the admission charter of the Heart School and to understand the admission rules for higher education institutions, including the transfer rate, rules for professional assignment, etc.
The rules for the allocation of professions refer to three modes of professional admission, namely, professional preference, grade priority and professional grade differentials, following a transfer from higher education.
The specific modalities used in higher education institutions are specified in the Statute of Admission.
However, there are also some institutions of higher education where the principle of admission is given priority and there is no difference between the levels of specialization.
In other words, candidates in the range are queued according to their total score, and when the score does not reach the first professional voluntary intake score, it depends on whether the second professional voluntary intake score has been reached, so that it is pushed until the last professional volunteer is accepted, and there is no grade differential between professional volunteers.
The so-called “professional differential” is the “professional differential” in the selection of candidates for a different professional voluntary examination, which is determined by the grade of one or more of the points published in the by-laws of admission.
This is the difference between the scores of the first and non-first professional voluntary students admitted to the Institute and the difference between the levels of the various professional volunteers, i.e., three, two, one.
For example.
On the assumption that the students will take the post-secondary examination, 560 points have been taken for professional volunteering: computers, international trade, automation, mechanical engineering, e-commerce, and professional admissions to the post-secondary level A have a professional differential of 2 points, 1 point, 1 point and 0 points.
When a professional assignment is made, if the first professional volunteer meets the requirements for professional admission and there is a planned balance of the profession, he is admitted to the “computer” profession; if the computer is not accepted, his score will be reduced by two points to determine whether the qualification for professional admission is met by ranking the first professional volunteer for “international trade” according to the 558 score; if it remains unsatisfied, the third professional voluntary “automated” admission will be reduced by one point (i.e. 557); if it remains unsatisfied, the fourth professional admission will be reduced by a further fraction (i.e., 556) and the subsequent professional will not be reduced by such deduction.
Different universities have different levels of specialization.
With the spread of parallel volunteering, many higher education institutions have now abolished professional grades, but some of them have retained this method this year, which, according to the admissions charter published by the respective schools, has been marked by more than 20 universities.
For example, Sichuan University of Agriculture, Shandong University of Science and Technology, Heilongjiang University of Medicine, Jiangsu University of Technology, Jiangxi University of Teacher Training, Chengdu College of Medicine, Northeast Power University, Sumi University, Nanjing University of Medicine, Nanjing Industrial University, Ningxia University, Shandong University of Technology, Chinese Civil Aviation Flight School, etc.
Each university has a different level of specialization in these institutions.
Some higher education institutions have grades in each specialty, such as the University of Ningxia, where the files have been placed and accepted according to the order in which the candidates filed their professional volunteer, in descending order of fraction.
Some universities, on the other hand, have different professional grades between them.
For example, at the Central University, the total difference in professional voluntary rank is 4 points, i.e. 3 points for first professional voluntary and other professional voluntary levels, no difference between other professional volunteers, considered parallel voluntary, and 1 point between other professional voluntary and transfer professional volunteer levels.
When making a voluntary contribution, candidates and parents must carefully read the admission policy of the reported school and see whether there is a difference in professional grades, what the difference is, and, while taking due account of the points, a reasonable analysis of the schools and professions to be selected, if the admissions are explicitly made by a grade difference in the by-laws of the institution, and when selecting a profession, the candidates must take care of the gradients between the professions and increase the intake rate.
